<br>
Hi all; <br>
<br>
Take a minute and analyze a &quot;normal&quot; melee centric boss mob fight, from a melee point of view, with everybody doing as much damage as they can w/o taking aggro from the MT. <br>
<br>
Relevant characteristics: <br>
Main tank: stands in front of mob, as close as possible, maintains aggro via taunt, procs/effects, and proximity. Does very low melee damage due to mob's avoidance skills (dodge parry block riposte), but can do substantial damage if well damage sheilded. Primary characteristic is high hp, high taunt weapons, ability to control mob direction. Optional secondary characteristic: immunity to frontal stun from melee. <br>
<br>
Rogues: stand directly behind mob at max melee range, mash backstab key and evade. DPS output limited only by quality of weapons, haste, ATK, and short interruptions due to evade. <br>
<br>
Monks: stand directly behind mob at max melee range, mash special attack key, FD periodically to clear all aggro. DPS output limited only by quality of weapons, haste, ATK, and short interruptions due to FD. <br>
<br>
All Other Melee (rangers = archery, not melee for this exercise): stand directly behind mob at max melee range. Primary DPS output limiter is the need to avoid stealing aggro from MT, so use of sub-optimal weapons and/or cycling attack on and off is necessary. <br>
<br>
So what does this suggest? <br>
-increasing a warrior MTs DPS and/or net taunt ability would allow less frequent evades/FDs by monks/rogues and less cycling by other melee. Relatively large increase in melee aggregate DPS from this, from extra DPS on non-MT warriors, reduced need for aggro reduction by monk/rog, less cycling by knight classes. Since DPS is much higher for rog/monk, they end up doing even MORE damage than other melee anyay... i.e. same extra attack time + higher dps = more dmg. Somewhat counterintuitive. <br>
<br>
-decreasing warrior DPS and/or net taunt ability, including going from dual wield to 1h + non-taunt shield, would reduce the aggregate DPS of melee classes (for the same reason mentioned above), and potentially other DD types. This would serve to better &quot;balance&quot; the melee classes effective DPS output, but with other, more unpleasant side effects... Would greatly increase the viability of knights and/or monks as warrior replacements as MTs, and generally trivialize the warrior class. <br>
<br>
-increasing a warrior MTs mitigation and/or HP would make fights more predictable, and increase/cement their selection as MT. Reduces the healing load, perhaps allowing other priest classes into the CH chain with clerics. Does nothing for non-MT warriors in pure melee fights; improves them for rampage tanking and/or AE DD/DoT situations. <br>
<br>
-decreasing a warrior MTs mitigation and/or HP... don't wanna think about this one, outcome fairly obvious. <br>
<br>
-increasing a warrior MTs avoidance ability (via block, skill caps, etc) would allow longer or less deep CH chains WITH an increase in risk of MT loss; can decrease the healing load with an increase in uncertainty, marginally increases the need for non-MT warriors as &quot;backups&quot;. Increases which affect other classes (like adding block + mitigation to all shields useable by monks/knights) while also improving warriors would make them even more desireable was MT replacements, due to their superiour ability to generate aggro + newly improved reduction in net damage taken. <br>
<br>
-decreasing a warrior MTs avoidance... ibid, mitigation. <br>
<br>
Doesn't look all that straightforward. :/ Some other possibilities for improving warrior viability, that may/may not have similar drawbacks and/or severe nerf factors: <br>
<br>
-increase non-damage-dealing &quot;downtime&quot; incurred by evade/FD; reduces effective disparity in melee DPS directly. <br>
<br>
-remove/reduce taunt factor of SK and paladin spells; reduces their viability as MTs relative to warriors. <br>
<br>
-add significant taunt to slam/bash/kick; allows warriors to generate aggro on par with hybrid classes, but will increase disparity in effective DPS as noted above. <br>
<br>
-reduce effectiveness of mob avoidance skills vs. warriors; promising, would enhance warriors as MTs, may suffer from enhanced taunt issue however. <br>
<br>
-decrease proximity component in mob hate, or increase hate due to melee damage... could be ugly.  <br>
<br>
Hrm... need more time to ponder. A &quot;GOOD&quot; fix for warriors doesn't seem all that straightforward/trivial... just thought I'd toss in some thoughts and observations. <br>
<br>
RdT. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uvaraho1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Varaho1</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 610<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/23/02 12:13:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1056.topic&index=107>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: musings...</span><hr size=1> But Remf what else can they do with warriors other than those? Its not as if we have a spellbook  to upgrade, or skills to tweak. That list above is all of the forces that could possibly balance our class. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=170513">Varaho Carnicero</a>
