<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   Monks start out with 67% of the HP of a Warrior with maxed stamina at level 60. With both fully max geared and AAXPed the Monk now has 85% of the Warrior's HP. The gap is narrowed by 18%.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Actually, the gap has closed by much more than 18%. Monks start out with 66.666~% of a warriors hp, which means that the warrior has 50% more hp than a monk naturally. Add up all the buffs, AA, and +hp items and the warrior now has 17% greater hp instead of 50%. That is not a trivial difference.<br>
<br>
Here's my take on the things that need to be done to balance <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  the game</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, not just a specific class.<br>
<br>
1.) Either have +hp items scale the effecitve hp a class recieves based on the STA multipier, or just don't make stupid @#%$ ALL/ALL items with +125 hp them. Go back and retro change all items (yea right) to fix this.<br>
<br>
2.) Fix the DPS heirarchy to something sane. 80/100/120/140 would be nice. 85/100/160/200 is just @#%$ stupid. Have they not realised by now that offensive power is the single greatest ability in the game?<br>
<br>
3.) Fix mitigation AC, and do so based on armor type. A cleric(plate) should take less damage per hit than a ranger (chain) but get hit more often. <br>
<br>
4.) Realise the relative merits of offensive and defensive abilities.<br>
<br>
Here's a thought to leave you with.<br>
<br>
There are 2 groups of people attempting to kill a kunark dragon. Which of these 2 groups will kill it easier and with fewer deaths?<br>
<br>
6 manaburn wizards.<br>
12 clerics with a 1 second cast, 100 mana cost CH<br>
<br>
Seems stupid in that context doesn't it?<br>
<br>
<br>
EDIT: to reconcile the DPS differences amongst the melee classes, I really think they need to LOWER monk and rogue DPS instead of raising everyone else's melee DPS. That would further seperate the melees from the damage dealing casters, would trivialize more content, and would cause more long term problems.<br>
 <p><A href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14686"> Graal MacBladefury</A><BR>
Crusader of Brell<BR></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ugraalthedorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Graal the Dorf</A> at: 8/23/02 3:26:17 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=remfdatroll>Remf da Troll</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 273<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/23/02 3:35:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1056.topic&index=112>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haha</span><hr size=1> Hey Grak-<br>
<br>
Another, perhaps more balanced way to reduce the dps disparity between monks/rogues and other melee would be to reduce the effectiveness of their aggro reduction/elimination.  That's what really allows them to open up and do their massive damage.  Reducing the effect of their aggro reduction would require them to throttle back damage or overaggro the way other melee classes (less rangers with jolt) do now.  Just adding DPS or taunt to a MT would actually just allow monk/rog to do even MORE damage, since they'd be able to feign/evade that much less...<br>
<br>
Putting in a longer delay-before-resuming-attack in after evade/fd would do the same thing- reduced their effective DPS.  You could also reduce the &quot;range&quot; on their weapons to increase the effect of proximity aggro, but that'd be somewhat difficult to implement maybe...<br>
<br>
Hrm.  More thinking needed.<br>
